A vivid view of Yellowstone’s Norris Geyser Basin, featuring milky blue hot springs bordered by bright orange, red, and yellow mineral deposits. The barren, rocky terrain contrasts sharply with the colorful thermal pools, with only a few scattered evergreen trees dotting the scene. The background reveals more steaming pools and colorful runoff channels, highlighting the geothermal activity of the area.

This image shows a close-up view of a geothermal pool with mineral-rich water in shades of yellow, green, and rusty orange. The pool is bordered by sinter deposits forming irregular, crusty edges, characteristic of hot spring runoff zones. The water’s coloration comes from a mix of dissolved minerals and heat-loving microorganisms. The surrounding ground is a dry, pale, and cracked surface, contrasting with the vivid pool interior, likely part of a thermal feature in Yellowstone National Park.

Steam rises subtly from the crystal-clear water, framed by a backdrop of evergreen forest and a partly cloudy summer sky. The striking contrast of colors showcases the park’s unique geothermal beauty.
